In C++, you can stop a thread by allowing it to naturally finish its execution or by signaling it to exit gracefully. Forcibly terminating a thread is generally discouraged, as it can lead to resource leaks and undefined behavior.

The most common method to stop a thread is to let it complete its task by returning from its thread function. When a thread function returns, the thread is automatically terminated. This approach is suitable when you have a well-defined task for the thread, and it should exit when that task is complete.

```cpp
void worker_thread() {
    // Thread work
}

int main() {
    std::thread t(worker_thread);

    // Do some work...

    t.join();  // Wait for the thread to finish

    return 0;
}
```

Alternatively, you can use a shared flag variable to signal the thread to stop. The thread periodically checks this flag and exits when it's set. This method provides more control over when the thread stops.

```cpp
std::atomic stop_flag(false);

void worker_thread() {
    while (!stop_flag) {
        // Thread work
    }
}

int main() {
    std::thread t(worker_thread);

    // Do some work...

    stop_flag = true;  // Signal the thread to stop
    t.join();  // Wait for the thread to finish

    return 0;
}
```

Always ensure proper synchronization and coordination when using flags to control thread termination to avoid race conditions.

Remember that forcibly terminating threads using methods like `std::terminate` or `std::quick_exit` should be avoided as they can result in unpredictable consequences. Instead, design your threads to exit gracefully based on well-defined conditions, which helps maintain code reliability and stability.

